# Memory Management Standards (Embedded)

This document defines memory management standards for embedded firmware: allocation policies, stack discipline, buffer management, and leak prevention.

---

## Core Principle: No Dynamic Allocation After Init

All memory must be statically allocated or allocated from fixed pools during system initialization. After `main()` enters its run loop, no `malloc`, `calloc`, `realloc`, or `free` calls are permitted.

**Rationale**: Dynamic allocation introduces fragmentation, non-deterministic timing, and failure modes that are unacceptable in long-running embedded systems.

---

## Allocation Policy

### Permitted Patterns

| Pattern | When to Use | Example |
|---------|-------------|---------|
| Static global | Singleton resources, device drivers | `static uint8_t uart_rx_buf[256];` |
| Static local | Per-function persistent state | `static uint32_t last_timestamp;` |
| Pool allocator | Variable-count fixed-size objects | Message pool, connection pool |
| Stack local | Short-lived, small (< 256 bytes) | Local calculation buffers |

### Prohibited Patterns

| Pattern | Risk | Alternative |
|---------|------|-------------|
| `malloc` / `free` in run loop | Fragmentation, OOM | Static or pool allocation |
| VLA (variable-length array) | Stack overflow | Fixed-size array with bounds check |
| `alloca` | Stack overflow, non-portable | Fixed-size local buffer |
| Recursive functions | Unbounded stack | Iterative with explicit stack |
| Large stack locals (> 256 bytes) | Stack overflow | Static buffer or pool |

