## Memory Pool Design

### Pool Allocator Requirements

```c
/* Pool allocator interface */
typedef struct {
    void *base;
    size_t block_size;
    size_t block_count;
    size_t used_count;
    uint32_t *free_bitmap;
} mem_pool_t;

/* Initialize pool from static buffer */
void pool_init(mem_pool_t *pool, void *buffer, size_t block_size, size_t count);

/* Allocate a block -- returns NULL if exhausted */
void *pool_alloc(mem_pool_t *pool);

/* Free a block back to pool */
void pool_free(mem_pool_t *pool, void *ptr);

/* Diagnostic: current utilization */
size_t pool_used(const mem_pool_t *pool);
size_t pool_available(const mem_pool_t *pool);
```

### Pool Sizing Rules

| Rule | Rationale |
|------|-----------|
| Size pools for worst-case concurrent usage + 20% | Headroom for bursts |
| Log pool high-water mark at runtime | Detect sizing errors before OOM |
| Pool exhaustion returns NULL (never blocks in ISR) | ISR must not block |
| Test with pool artificially reduced to 50% | Verify graceful degradation |

